article.headline: Seven Spurs score in double figures
article.linkText: Spurs beat Hornets to win 16 of last 17
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The San Antonio Spurs found plenty of ways to score while frustrating New Orleans with their typically stingy defense. Tim Duncan and Bruce Bowen each scored 15 points to lead seven San Antonio players in double figures, and the Spurs defeated the Hornets 94-84 on Friday night for their 16th win in 17 games. New Orleans bettered San Antonio in several statistical categories such as rebounds (52-46) and turnovers (12-20) but simply couldn't hit shots, finishing at 32 percent from the field, compared to the Spurs' 52 percent shooting. "Our main goal was making sure we could get a hand up on each and every shot," Bowen said. "We're just trying to do what we do and improve on that, and that's defense, because there will be nights when we don't shoot well." Hedo Turkoglu scored 13, Tony Parker and Ron Mercer each scored 12, and Rasho Nesterovic and Devin Brown each added 10 for San Antonio. "I didn't have the greatest of nights, but guys stepped in and made things happen," Duncan said. "That's what we've been doing all season. We've been finding ways to make things work." Baron Davis led the Hornets with 19 points, but early foul trouble limited his playing time and he struggled to connect on 3-pointers (2-of-9) as he tried to help New Orleans overcome a double-digit deficit late in the game. Guarded mostly by Bowen, he finished 7-of-21 form the field. "I wanted to be a pest. I wanted to make him shoot over my length and not give him a lot of uncontested 3s," Bowen said. The Hornets put up 97 shots, compared to 66 for San Antonio, and managed to get as close as 87-79 when Davis hit a 3-pointer with 2:10 left. But Brown converted an up-and-under layup on the other end, then followed that with a pair of free throws to put the game out of reach. Many of New Orleans' missed shots came from its starting frontcourt of Jamaal Magloire, P.J. Brown and George Lynch, who combined to go 7-for-29. That helped San Antonio open a 20-point lead in the third quarter. The Spurs "make it difficult for everybody to score and, ultimately, that was our problem tonight. It's a great defensive club," Hornets coach Tim Floyd said. Hornets guard David Wesley, normally a solid outside shooter, also had trouble scoring as he shot 3-of-14. But he was reluctant to give the Spurs' defense credit. "I didn't feel the kind of pressure the percentages show," Wesley said. "It was our inability to hit shots." Davis was the only Hornet scoring with consistency early on, but he committed his fourth foul in the first minute of the second half and went to the bench for the remainder of the third period. Floyd appeared frustrated by the officiating, pumping his fist and yelling at the officials several times. In the fourth quarter, he was called for a technical foul as he stormed out near center court while assistants held him back. He was angry after no foul was called when Wesley and Parker tangled as they dove for a loose ball, with Wesley getting the ball first. San Antonio scored from inside and outside all night, with all five starters reaching double figures before seven minutes had elapsed in the third quarter. Parker scored six straight points early in the second half, hitting a layup as he was fouled, then a 3-pointer, to give San Antonio a 55-38 lead. When Bowen hit a 3-pointer about midway through the third quarter, the Spurs were 7-of-9 from behind the 3-point line and had a 66-46 lead. They finished 7-for-11 on 3s. "I didn't expect to get the lead we got," Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said. "They had a night they could not knock it down and another night they'd probably make a lot more. We just shot a little better than they did." Reserve guard Darrell Armstrong responded to extended playing time by scoring 12 points in the third period, including a pull-up 3 after getting his third steal, as the Hornets tried to claw back into the game with an 11-2 run. When Armstrong found Wesley for a fast-break layup, the Hornets cut it to 68-57. Duncan snapped the run with a free throw, then Mercer hit a 20-foot jumper to push the lead back to 14. Armstrong finished with 16 points for New Orleans, and Magloire had a strong fourth quarter to finish with 12 points and 11 rebounds. Stacy Augmon and Robert Traylor came off the bench to score 10 each for New Orleans.

Game notes
Former Knicks point guard Charlie Ward, signed late Thursday by the Spurs, was not in New Orleans. Popovich said he expected to meet with Ward in San Antonio on Saturday, and that Ward likely would play within the next few games. "I really don't want him to play until he feels comfortable. I'm really not too big on just throwing somebody in there." ... The Spurs are 14-2 against Eastern Conference teams this season.
